# azure-service-bus Best Practices

This document outlines critical best practices for using Azure Service Bus with the Azure.Messaging.ServiceBus SDK. Following these guidelines will help you build robust, efficient, and maintainable messaging solutions.

## Code Organization and Structure

### Use Dependency Injection for ServiceBusClient

**Why:** Registering `ServiceBusClient`, `Sender`, and `Receiver` as singletons ensures optimal connection reuse and resource management.

```csharp
// ❌ BAD: Creating a new instance for every operation
var client = new ServiceBusClient(connectionString);
var sender = client.CreateSender("queue-name");

// ✅ GOOD: Register as singleton in Startup.cs
builder.Services.AddAzureClients(clientBuilder => {
    clientBuilder.AddServiceBusClient(connectionString);
});
```

## Common Patterns and Anti-patterns

### Use ServiceBusProcessor for Message Handling

**Why:** `ServiceBusProcessor` simplifies message processing and provides reliable message handling with built-in concurrency control.

```csharp
// ✅ GOOD: Using ServiceBusProcessor for handling messages
var processor = client.CreateProcessor("queue-name", new ServiceBusProcessorOptions {
    MaxConcurrentCalls = 5,
    AutoCompleteMessages = false,
    PrefetchCount = 20
});

processor.ProcessMessageAsync += async args => {
    // Process message
    await args.CompleteMessageAsync(args.Message);
};

processor.ProcessErrorAsync += async args => {
    // Log error
};

await processor.StartProcessingAsync();
```

### Avoid Using Sessions Unless Necessary

**Why:** Sessions limit parallelism and should only be used when strict FIFO ordering is required.

```csharp
// ❌ BAD: Using sessions unnecessarily
var sessionProcessor = client.CreateSessionProcessor("queue-name", new ServiceBusSessionProcessorOptions {
    MaxConcurrentSessions = 5
});

// ✅ GOOD: Use sessions only when FIFO is critical
var sessionProcessor = client.CreateSessionProcessor("queue-name");
```

## Performance Considerations

### Batch Sends for Efficiency

**Why:** Batching messages reduces the number of network calls, improving throughput.

```csharp
// ✅ GOOD: Using CreateMessageBatchAsync for batch sending
var batch = await sender.CreateMessageBatchAsync();
foreach (var message in messages) {
    if (!batch.TryAddMessage(message)) {
        await sender.SendMessageAsync(batch);
        batch = await sender.CreateMessageBatchAsync();
        batch.TryAddMessage(message);
    }
}
await sender.SendMessageAsync(batch);
```

### Configure PrefetchCount and MaxConcurrentCalls

**Why:** Properly configuring these options can significantly reduce latency and improve throughput.

```csharp
// ✅ GOOD: Configuring prefetch and concurrency settings
var processor = client.CreateProcessor("queue-name", new ServiceBusProcessorOptions {
    MaxConcurrentCalls = 10,
    PrefetchCount = 50,
    AutoCompleteMessages = false
});
```

## Common Pitfalls and Gotchas

### Disable AutoCompleteMessages

**Why:** Disabling `AutoCompleteMessages` allows explicit control over message settlement, preventing message loss.

```csharp
// ❌ BAD: Leaving AutoCompleteMessages enabled
var processor = client.CreateProcessor("queue-name", new ServiceBusProcessorOptions {
    AutoCompleteMessages = true
});

// ✅ GOOD: Disable AutoCompleteMessages for explicit control
var processor = client.CreateProcessor("queue-name", new ServiceBusProcessorOptions {
    AutoCompleteMessages = false
});
```

### Avoid SAS Tokens for Authentication

**Why:** Use Microsoft Entra ID (Managed Identity) for better security and management.

```csharp
// ❌ BAD: Using SAS tokens for authentication
var client = new ServiceBusClient(connectionString, new ServiceBusClientOptions {
    Credential = new AzureSasCredential("your-sas-token")
});

// ✅ GOOD: Use Managed Identity for authentication
var client = new ServiceBusClient("your-service-bus-namespace.servicebus.windows.net", new DefaultAzureCredential());
```

## Testing Approaches

### Use In-Memory Testing for Unit Tests

**Why:** In-memory testing allows for quick and isolated tests of your message handling logic without needing an actual Service Bus instance.

```csharp
// ✅ GOOD: Mocking ServiceBusClient for unit tests
var mockClient = new Mock<ServiceBusClient>();
var mockSender = new Mock<ServiceBusSender>();
mockClient.Setup(c => c.CreateSender(It.IsAny<string>())).Returns(mockSender.Object);

// Test your message sending logic here
```

## Conclusion

By following these best practices, you will enhance your Azure Service Bus implementations, ensuring they are efficient, maintainable, and scalable. Always prioritize using the latest SDK features and patterns to avoid deprecated practices as the Azure ecosystem evolves.